00:00:15,740 --> 00:00:18,620
Let's talk about conservation of charge a little bit.

4
00:00:22,200 --> 00:00:24,810
The most naive version is that

5
00:00:24,810 --> 00:00:27,420
the amount of charge in the world,

6
00:00:27,420 --> 00:00:28,720
whatever the world means,

7
00:00:28,720 --> 00:00:30,740
doesn't change.

8
00:00:30,740 --> 00:00:32,479
It just stays the same.

9
00:00:33,540 --> 00:00:35,320
That's the most naive version of it.

10
00:00:35,700 --> 00:00:36,280
Now,

11
00:00:36,280 --> 00:00:38,420
if that were all there were to it,

12
00:00:38,420 --> 00:00:43,500
then it really wouldn't say very much.

13
00:00:44,160 --> 00:00:47,410
If a charge disappeared over

14
00:00:47,410 --> 00:00:50,660
here and reappeared on Alpha Centauri

15
00:00:50,660 --> 00:00:52,720
at exactly the same instant of time,

16
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:53,380
exactly,

17
00:00:54,120 --> 00:00:54,940
of course,

18
00:00:54,940 --> 00:00:56,400
we have to worry about relativity

19
00:00:56,400 --> 00:00:56,900
and the fact that it's going

20
00:00:56,900 --> 00:00:57,400
to be a very long time.

21
00:00:57,400 --> 00:00:58,560
The same instant of time

22
00:00:58,560 --> 00:00:59,720
may be a little bit confusing,

23
00:00:59,920 --> 00:01:03,480
but let's get a little pre-relativistic.

24
00:01:03,860 --> 00:01:06,520
If a charge disappeared over here

25
00:01:06,520 --> 00:01:09,180
and reappeared on Alpha Centauri instantaneously,

26
00:01:09,800 --> 00:01:12,740
we would say charge is conserved by that definition.

27
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:15,320
That total charge doesn't change.

28
00:01:15,760 --> 00:01:20,020
But we aren't on Alpha Centauri.

29
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:21,440
It's too far away for

30
00:01:21,440 --> 00:01:22,800
us to know what's happening there.

31
00:01:23,300 --> 00:01:26,120
And so in that sense,

32
00:01:26,120 --> 00:01:27,340
if that's all there was,

33
00:01:27,340 --> 00:01:27,360
then we're going to be able

34
00:01:27,360 --> 00:01:27,380
to do a lot of things.

35
00:01:27,380 --> 00:01:27,720
But if that was the case,

36
00:01:27,720 --> 00:01:28,300
if we were to go to charge conservation,

37
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:29,940
it wouldn't tell us anything.

38
00:01:30,480 --> 00:01:32,140
It wouldn't tell us anything at all.

39
00:01:32,220 --> 00:01:32,460
Okay,

40
00:01:32,460 --> 00:01:33,800
if we could get to Alpha

41
00:01:33,800 --> 00:01:35,140
Centauri and check the charges there,

42
00:01:35,260 --> 00:01:37,020
we could go to Beta Centauri,

43
00:01:37,020 --> 00:01:38,080
or Gamma Centauri,

44
00:01:38,140 --> 00:01:40,220
or the next galaxy over,

45
00:01:40,220 --> 00:01:40,940
or whatever,

46
00:01:41,560 --> 00:01:43,580
and we would have exactly the same problem,

47
00:01:44,160 --> 00:01:46,200
that within our laboratory,

48
00:01:46,200 --> 00:01:50,000
charge conservation wouldn't mean anything.

49
00:01:50,740 --> 00:01:52,480
We'd have no way of checking it.

50
00:01:53,380 --> 00:01:53,860
Now,

51
00:01:53,860 --> 00:01:55,780
what is the way that we check it?

52
00:01:55,780 --> 00:01:58,180
Can charge disappear from the laboratory?

53
00:01:58,660 --> 00:01:59,200
Yes,

54
00:01:59,200 --> 00:02:01,040
charge can disappear from the laboratory.

55
00:02:01,740 --> 00:02:04,000
It can reappear outside the laboratory.

56
00:02:04,820 --> 00:02:06,280
But in order to do so,

57
00:02:06,280 --> 00:02:09,800
it has to pass through the walls of the laboratory.

58
00:02:10,380 --> 00:02:13,850
And so some detector set up at the walls

59
00:02:13,850 --> 00:02:17,320
of the laboratory to monitor the flow of charge.

60
00:02:17,820 --> 00:02:21,860
What do detectors do?

61
00:02:22,060 --> 00:02:24,500
They would ring bells or detect.

62
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:25,820
That's what detectors do.

63
00:02:25,940 --> 00:02:26,340
They detect.

64
00:02:26,800 --> 00:02:27,840
They would detect,

65
00:02:27,840 --> 00:02:28,360
ring bells,

66
00:02:28,360 --> 00:02:30,270
and we would know that charge

67
00:02:30,270 --> 00:02:32,180
passed from the inside to the outside.

68
00:02:33,460 --> 00:02:37,780
That idea that conservation means more than just the

69
00:02:37,780 --> 00:02:42,100
algebraic sum of the charges in the world doesn't change.

70
00:02:42,340 --> 00:02:44,970
But it means that there's a concept

71
00:02:44,970 --> 00:02:47,600
that when charge does disappear from a place,

72
00:02:48,430 --> 00:02:52,000
it identifiably moves through the walls of the system,

73
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,380
through the boundaries of the system,

74
00:02:54,500 --> 00:02:57,500
that gets quantified in the

75
00:02:57,500 --> 00:03:00,500
idea of local charge conservation,

76
00:03:02,359 --> 00:03:04,069
or the idea of a

77
00:03:04,069 --> 00:03:05,780
current as well as a charge.

78
00:03:06,100 --> 00:03:08,080
A current is a flow of charge.

79
00:03:08,840 --> 00:03:11,080
So another way to say it

80
00:03:11,080 --> 00:03:13,320
is if charge disappears from this room,

81
00:03:13,560 --> 00:03:15,570
it's because a current flowed through

82
00:03:15,570 --> 00:03:17,580
somehow the boundaries of the room.

83
00:03:18,220 --> 00:03:19,920
That's the only way it can happen,

84
00:03:19,920 --> 00:03:22,200
and a current flowing through the boundaries of the

85
00:03:22,200 --> 00:03:24,480
room is detectable at the walls of the room.

86
00:03:24,500 --> 00:03:28,160
So let's see if we can quantify that,

87
00:03:28,160 --> 00:03:29,480
not just quantify it,

88
00:03:29,480 --> 00:03:30,920
formalize it,

89
00:03:31,020 --> 00:03:34,060
turn it into a mathematical statement of some sort,

90
00:03:34,899 --> 00:03:36,689
and then check with our little

91
00:03:36,689 --> 00:03:38,480
theory that we made up about charge,

92
00:03:40,100 --> 00:03:40,620
that,

93
00:03:40,620 --> 00:03:40,980
well,

94
00:03:40,980 --> 00:03:42,400
we'll go back to it,

95
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:44,480
whether it satisfies that criterion.

96
00:03:45,720 --> 00:03:46,380
All right,

97
00:03:46,380 --> 00:03:46,980
first of all,

98
00:03:46,980 --> 00:03:48,320
there's the concept of charge.

99
00:03:48,460 --> 00:03:48,700
Yes?

100
00:03:49,459 --> 00:03:51,559
Is this particularly different than

101
00:03:51,559 --> 00:03:53,660
a similar statement about mass?

102
00:03:54,739 --> 00:03:55,260
No,

103
00:03:55,260 --> 00:03:58,520
it is not particularly different than statements about mass.

104
00:03:59,000 --> 00:03:59,520
Now,

105
00:03:59,520 --> 00:04:00,940
the difference is that,

106
00:04:00,940 --> 00:04:03,000
I'll tell you what the difference is.

107
00:04:03,480 --> 00:04:06,580
Mass by itself in a relativistic theory doesn't really,

108
00:04:06,580 --> 00:04:07,700
is not a conserved quantity.

109
00:04:07,800 --> 00:04:09,900
Energy is the corresponding conserved quantity.

110
00:04:10,340 --> 00:04:10,980
All right,

111
00:04:10,980 --> 00:04:11,680
energy,

112
00:04:11,680 --> 00:04:14,660
and it comes along with another conserved quantity,

113
00:04:14,760 --> 00:04:16,440
or three other conserved quantities,

114
00:04:16,440 --> 00:04:17,240
which are called momentum,

115
00:04:17,240 --> 00:04:19,360
and they form a complex.

116
00:04:19,980 --> 00:04:22,780
But each one of them is separately conserved,

117
00:04:22,780 --> 00:04:24,380
and each one of them has a flow.

118
00:04:25,840 --> 00:04:26,300
Now,

119
00:04:26,300 --> 00:04:26,900
in fact,

120
00:04:26,900 --> 00:04:30,360
the momentum is the flow of energy.

121
00:04:32,500 --> 00:04:33,900
But what's the flow of momentum?

122
00:04:34,420 --> 00:04:36,080
And that's something else called stress.

123
00:04:36,600 --> 00:04:37,060
Now,

124
00:04:37,060 --> 00:04:38,040
whether we'll get to the stress,

125
00:04:38,040 --> 00:04:40,120
it's called stress,

126
00:04:40,220 --> 00:04:42,090
not the kind of stress that you feel

127
00:04:42,090 --> 00:04:43,960
when you know you've lied to your wife,

128
00:04:44,080 --> 00:04:45,340
but then she's going to catch you,

129
00:04:45,380 --> 00:04:48,610
but the kind of stress that a material

130
00:04:48,610 --> 00:04:51,840
object experiences when a force is imposed on it.

131
00:04:53,140 --> 00:04:54,480
Did I say something about momentum?

132
00:04:54,500 --> 00:04:57,180
Of you having lied and...

133
00:04:57,180 --> 00:04:57,600
No,

134
00:04:57,600 --> 00:04:57,860
no,

135
00:04:57,860 --> 00:04:58,680
I didn't mean that.

136
00:05:03,480 --> 00:05:04,000
What?

137
00:05:05,900 --> 00:05:06,840
This is 2000,

138
00:05:06,840 --> 00:05:07,760
you can't see that.

139
00:05:08,020 --> 00:05:08,780
This is two...

140
00:05:10,480 --> 00:05:10,960
2008,

141
00:05:10,960 --> 00:05:11,840
you can't do that?

142
00:05:12,120 --> 00:05:13,720
The 1960s.

143
00:05:14,140 --> 00:05:16,460
I stopped doing it in the 1960s,

144
00:05:16,460 --> 00:05:16,820
that's right.

145
00:05:18,040 --> 00:05:21,440
I stopped doing almost everything interesting in the...

146
00:05:22,480 --> 00:05:23,000
Yeah,

147
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:23,760
so where were we?

148
00:05:23,760 --> 00:05:25,680
We were talking about charge flow,

149
00:05:25,960 --> 00:05:28,500
and the first concept is charge density.

150
00:05:28,960 --> 00:05:29,480
Now,

151
00:05:29,480 --> 00:05:31,300
density is not the motion of charge,

152
00:05:31,520 --> 00:05:33,540
it's just a local version of the

153
00:05:33,540 --> 00:05:35,560
idea of how much charge is there.

154
00:05:35,880 --> 00:05:39,200
Local means it's identified with a small region of space.

155
00:05:39,860 --> 00:05:42,880
There's the idea of charge density.

156
00:05:43,360 --> 00:05:46,340
Charge density is just locally,

157
00:05:46,340 --> 00:05:48,540
at some particular location,

158
00:05:48,780 --> 00:05:52,740
the charge per unit volume that's present.

159
00:05:53,760 --> 00:05:53,940
Now,

160
00:05:53,940 --> 00:05:55,160
to define it precisely,

161
00:05:55,920 --> 00:05:57,900
we do a little bit of calculus

162
00:05:57,900 --> 00:05:59,880
and a little bit of limiting notions.

163
00:06:00,400 --> 00:06:04,120
We take a little box around the surrounding point.

164
00:06:04,780 --> 00:06:07,260
We take the total charge in that box.

165
00:06:07,520 --> 00:06:09,760
Let's say the box is of size epsilon.

166
00:06:10,540 --> 00:06:11,660
It has a volume,

167
00:06:11,660 --> 00:06:12,520
epsilon cubed.

168
00:06:12,980 --> 00:06:15,100
We take the charge inside that box.

169
00:06:15,900 --> 00:06:16,980
Let's call it...

170
00:06:16,980 --> 00:06:18,540
What's a good name for charge?

171
00:06:18,660 --> 00:06:18,780
Q.

172
00:06:18,960 --> 00:06:22,200
Q is the standard terminology for electric charge.

173
00:06:22,900 --> 00:06:23,420
Q.

174
00:06:23,760 --> 00:06:24,920
Q inside the box.

175
00:06:25,160 --> 00:06:26,660
This is not Q of the world.

176
00:06:26,780 --> 00:06:28,120
This is Q of the box.

177
00:06:28,560 --> 00:06:30,860
We divide it by the volume of the box.

178
00:06:32,580 --> 00:06:35,880
And then we take the limit in which both...

179
00:06:35,880 --> 00:06:37,600
in which epsilon goes to zero,

180
00:06:37,720 --> 00:06:39,520
and of course also Q goes to zero.

181
00:06:39,760 --> 00:06:41,720
We take the limit of Q over epsilon

182
00:06:41,720 --> 00:06:43,380
as the box gets smaller and smaller,

183
00:06:43,880 --> 00:06:45,540
and that's called rho.

184
00:06:47,360 --> 00:06:48,520
Rho for density.

185
00:06:48,720 --> 00:06:50,450
I don't know why it's called rho

186
00:06:50,450 --> 00:06:52,180
and not D or delta or something else,

187
00:06:52,180 --> 00:06:54,000
but it's rho for density,

188
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:55,180
and it depends on position.

189
00:06:55,740 --> 00:06:56,420
Of course,

190
00:06:56,420 --> 00:06:57,760
it also depends on time.

191
00:06:58,040 --> 00:07:00,340
The density of charge can change with time.

192
00:07:00,780 --> 00:07:02,140
So whatever rho is,

193
00:07:02,140 --> 00:07:04,800
it depends on position and time.

194
00:07:06,380 --> 00:07:06,860
Okay.

195
00:07:07,060 --> 00:07:08,300
What do we do with rho?

196
00:07:08,600 --> 00:07:09,040
Well,

197
00:07:09,040 --> 00:07:09,720
if we know rho,

198
00:07:09,720 --> 00:07:11,440
we can say how much charge

199
00:07:11,440 --> 00:07:13,160
is in any region of space.

200
00:07:13,940 --> 00:07:15,320
In any region of space,

201
00:07:15,320 --> 00:07:17,460
let's take an arbitrary region of space now,

202
00:07:17,600 --> 00:07:18,360
with any shape,

203
00:07:18,360 --> 00:07:18,580
whatever,

204
00:07:19,159 --> 00:07:20,980
then the amount of charge in there,

205
00:07:21,460 --> 00:07:22,680
let's also call it Q,

206
00:07:22,840 --> 00:07:23,850
but it doesn't stand for

207
00:07:23,850 --> 00:07:24,860
the charge in a box now,

208
00:07:24,940 --> 00:07:26,760
it stands for the charge in a general region,

209
00:07:27,420 --> 00:07:31,100
is then equal to the integral over that region,

210
00:07:32,200 --> 00:07:33,600
let's call it D3x,

211
00:07:33,600 --> 00:07:34,600
meaning Dx,

212
00:07:34,600 --> 00:07:34,840
Dy,

213
00:07:34,840 --> 00:07:35,280
Dz,

214
00:07:35,900 --> 00:07:36,940
over that region,

215
00:07:36,940 --> 00:07:38,820
over the interior of that region of rho.

216
00:07:41,960 --> 00:07:42,940
And strictly speaking,

217
00:07:42,940 --> 00:07:44,180
we could take this to

218
00:07:44,180 --> 00:07:45,420
be the definition of charge density.

219
00:07:45,960 --> 00:07:47,590
It's the thing that you sum up

220
00:07:47,590 --> 00:07:49,220
or integrate over a region of space

221
00:07:49,220 --> 00:07:50,840
to find out how much charge is in there.

222
00:07:51,820 --> 00:07:53,660
The total charge in the universe,

223
00:07:53,940 --> 00:07:57,140
you integrate over everything in the world,

224
00:07:57,920 --> 00:07:59,360
all of volume,

225
00:07:59,360 --> 00:08:01,060
and that gives you the total charge in the universe,

226
00:08:01,200 --> 00:08:03,180
but usually that's a fairly useless concept,

227
00:08:03,380 --> 00:08:05,180
the total charge in the universe.

228
00:08:05,680 --> 00:08:09,420
Better integrate over the region of the laboratory,

229
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:11,240
and that will tell you how

230
00:08:11,240 --> 00:08:12,480
much charge is in your laboratory.

231
00:08:15,260 --> 00:08:15,820
Now,

232
00:08:15,820 --> 00:08:16,920
next concept,

233
00:08:16,920 --> 00:08:18,740
the flow of charge.

234
00:08:18,740 --> 00:08:21,300
The flow of charge is defined

235
00:08:21,300 --> 00:08:23,860
by a thing called the current.

236
00:08:24,640 --> 00:08:26,250
You're used to thinking

237
00:08:26,250 --> 00:08:27,860
about currents flowing through wires.

238
00:08:28,700 --> 00:08:30,230
We don't have to be

239
00:08:30,230 --> 00:08:31,760
thinking about currents flowing through wires,

240
00:08:31,900 --> 00:08:34,159
we're thinking about charges flowing through space,

241
00:08:34,340 --> 00:08:36,539
clouds of charge flowing through space.

242
00:08:37,500 --> 00:08:40,280
And to quantify the idea of a current,

243
00:08:42,880 --> 00:08:44,500
we take a little area,

244
00:08:45,860 --> 00:08:47,980
now this is an area in space,

245
00:08:47,980 --> 00:08:48,980
a little square,

246
00:08:50,520 --> 00:08:52,340
and we stand there and watch that square,

247
00:08:52,620 --> 00:08:55,580
and watch the charge passing through that little square.

248
00:08:55,680 --> 00:08:56,180
It's a little window,

249
00:08:56,180 --> 00:08:57,180
think of it as a window,

250
00:08:58,300 --> 00:08:59,240
small window,

251
00:08:59,819 --> 00:09:01,339
and charges go from one side

252
00:09:01,339 --> 00:09:02,860
of the window through the window

253
00:09:02,860 --> 00:09:04,600
out to the other side of the window.

254
00:09:05,560 --> 00:09:08,320
And we can ask how much charge

255
00:09:08,320 --> 00:09:11,080
goes through the window per unit time.

256
00:09:11,980 --> 00:09:13,640
We can wait one second and see

257
00:09:13,640 --> 00:09:15,300
how much charge goes through the window,

258
00:09:15,800 --> 00:09:16,280
count,

259
00:09:16,280 --> 00:09:17,300
take that charge,

260
00:09:17,300 --> 00:09:18,860
and divide it by the one second.

261
00:09:19,400 --> 00:09:21,300
But we can also do calculus,

262
00:09:21,380 --> 00:09:22,820
and we can go to the

263
00:09:22,820 --> 00:09:24,260
limit of a very small time interval.

264
00:09:24,820 --> 00:09:26,820
I think that's the last time I will say that,

265
00:09:26,820 --> 00:09:27,660
that we'll take limits.

266
00:09:27,920 --> 00:09:28,640
Just imagine,

267
00:09:28,640 --> 00:09:31,160
you know how to take limits.

268
00:09:33,120 --> 00:09:35,760
We study the amount of charge that

269
00:09:35,760 --> 00:09:38,400
goes through the window per unit time.

270
00:09:39,760 --> 00:09:41,200
Now that's not yet the current.

271
00:09:41,640 --> 00:09:44,160
The amount of charge that will go through that window

272
00:09:45,300 --> 00:09:48,180
will not only be proportional to the time element,

273
00:09:48,320 --> 00:09:50,520
the little time that you allow,

274
00:09:50,840 --> 00:09:52,820
but it will also be proportional to something else.

275
00:09:53,060 --> 00:09:53,460
What is it?

276
00:09:53,740 --> 00:09:55,700
The area of the window.

277
00:09:56,020 --> 00:09:57,860
The bigger the area of the window,

278
00:09:57,860 --> 00:09:59,100
the more charge will go through.

279
00:09:59,540 --> 00:10:00,780
So if we take the

280
00:10:00,780 --> 00:10:02,020
charge that goes through the window,

281
00:10:02,140 --> 00:10:02,360
again,

282
00:10:02,360 --> 00:10:03,100
let's call it q,

283
00:10:04,240 --> 00:10:06,740
and divide it by the area of the window,

284
00:10:06,840 --> 00:10:07,540
let's call it a,

285
00:10:08,260 --> 00:10:10,080
