00:37:34,300 --> 00:37:36,029
This in itself is invariant,

1022
00:37:36,420 --> 00:37:37,320
and so that would,

1023
00:37:37,320 --> 00:37:38,340
that would ensure,

1024
00:37:38,620 --> 00:37:41,280
or this term in a Lagrangian would be invariant.

1025
00:37:41,340 --> 00:37:43,300
What if it contained things like

1026
00:37:43,300 --> 00:37:44,220
d mu phi

1027
00:37:45,060 --> 00:37:46,940
times d mu phi star?

1028
00:37:48,540 --> 00:37:49,780
Still invariant,

1029
00:37:49,780 --> 00:37:50,460
because

1030
00:37:51,600 --> 00:37:54,080
if phi changes by a phase,

1031
00:37:54,380 --> 00:37:56,340
the derivative of phi changes by

1032
00:37:56,340 --> 00:37:57,580
exactly the same phase.

1033
00:37:58,560 --> 00:38:00,580
What about a thing like phi squared?

1034
00:38:03,080 --> 00:38:04,560
Is that invariant?

1035
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:06,600
No,

1036
00:38:06,700 --> 00:38:08,580
because phi squared,

1037
00:38:08,720 --> 00:38:10,080
what will happen to phi squared?

1038
00:38:10,260 --> 00:38:12,140
Phi squared will

1039
00:38:14,380 --> 00:38:16,880
get e to the two i epsilon

1040
00:38:16,880 --> 00:38:18,760
when you multiply phi by

1041
00:38:18,760 --> 00:38:19,760
e to the i epsilon.

1042
00:38:19,920 --> 00:38:20,600
Phi star phi,

1043
00:38:21,420 --> 00:38:23,540
the e to the i epsilons will cancel.

1044
00:38:23,920 --> 00:38:24,820
Phi squared,

1045
00:38:25,100 --> 00:38:25,920
they will not cancel.

1046
00:38:26,240 --> 00:38:27,300
So there are certainly things

1047
00:38:27,300 --> 00:38:28,600
which are not invariant.

1048
00:38:31,500 --> 00:38:33,160
If you had something like

