00:38:39,820 --> 00:38:40,300
No.

1052
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:43,280
But how about phi one squared plus phi two squared?

1053
00:38:43,740 --> 00:38:44,220
Yes.

1054
00:38:45,120 --> 00:38:45,820
All right,

1055
00:38:45,820 --> 00:38:46,060
so,

1056
00:38:47,620 --> 00:38:49,200
it's relatively easy

1057
00:38:49,200 --> 00:38:50,880
to look at a Lagrangian

1058
00:38:50,880 --> 00:38:53,060
and to see whether it's invariant

1059
00:38:53,060 --> 00:38:53,880
under this operation.

1060
00:38:54,260 --> 00:38:56,180
If written in terms of complex notations,

1061
00:38:56,660 --> 00:38:57,480
then it should involve

1062
00:38:58,060 --> 00:39:01,440
products of fields times complex conjugates.

1063
00:39:01,580 --> 00:39:03,600
If it's written in terms of the real components,

1064
00:39:04,020 --> 00:39:06,320
it should involve sums of squares

1065
00:39:06,320 --> 00:39:08,800
of things with index one

1066
00:39:08,800 --> 00:39:10,160
and things with index two.

1067
00:39:10,980 --> 00:39:12,660
Let's suppose that's the case.

1068
00:39:12,880 --> 00:39:15,540
Let's suppose that a Lagrangian is invariant.

1069
00:39:16,680 --> 00:39:18,040
Then there's a symmetry.

1070
00:39:19,060 --> 00:39:20,180
If there's a symmetry,

1071
00:39:20,380 --> 00:39:21,580
there's a conservation law.

1072
00:39:22,460 --> 00:39:25,360
Let's remember the form of such conservation laws.

1073
00:39:29,360 --> 00:39:30,800
There's a conserved quantity,

1074
00:39:30,940 --> 00:39:32,760
which is often called capital Q.

1075
00:39:32,960 --> 00:39:34,540
Sometimes it's even called small q,

1076
00:39:34,680 --> 00:39:36,660
and the reason it's called capital Q or small q

1077
00:39:36,660 --> 00:39:38,440
is because it's going to wind up being

1078
00:39:38,440 --> 00:39:39,760
some sort of charge.

1079
00:39:40,600 --> 00:39:43,780
So it's related to the thing we've already called charge.

1080
00:39:43,960 --> 00:39:44,800
But let's just call it q.

1081
00:39:44,800 --> 00:39:46,920
Sometimes called the Noether charge.

1082
00:39:48,660 --> 00:39:51,280
What you do is you sum over the whole system

1083
00:39:53,180 --> 00:39:54,540
the change.

1084
00:39:55,080 --> 00:39:57,700
This q is not the coordinates.

1085
00:39:59,240 --> 00:40:00,560
It's capital Q.

1086
00:40:00,560 --> 00:40:01,460
It's a charge.

1087
00:40:01,680 --> 00:40:03,180
You take the change

1088
00:40:05,480 --> 00:40:07,300
in the ith coordinate

1089
00:40:09,400 --> 00:40:11,640
and you multiply it

1090
00:40:12,700 --> 00:40:14,220
by the ith momentum.

1091
00:40:14,220 --> 00:40:16,080
Let's call it p sub i.

1092
00:40:17,780 --> 00:40:19,400
This is the canonical momentum

1093
00:40:19,400 --> 00:40:21,160
conjugate to q sub i.

1094
00:40:22,960 --> 00:40:24,350
Typically delta q sub i

1095
00:40:24,350 --> 00:40:25,740
will have an epsilon in it,

1096
00:40:25,740 --> 00:40:25,920
right?

1097
00:40:28,240 --> 00:40:29,480
Just drop the epsilon.

1098
00:40:30,160 --> 00:40:31,820
You can leave the epsilon there

1099
00:40:31,820 --> 00:40:34,020
and then throw it away at the end.

1100
00:40:34,340 --> 00:40:35,280
We don't need to worry.

1101
00:40:35,420 --> 00:40:36,900
It's just a numerical multiple,

1102
00:40:37,080 --> 00:40:38,980
a small numerical multiple of a quantity.

1103
00:40:39,340 --> 00:40:40,420
We could divide it.

1104
00:40:40,460 --> 00:40:41,720
We could divide out the epsilon.

1105
00:40:41,780 --> 00:40:43,340
The epsilon is of no importance,

1106
00:40:43,340 --> 00:40:43,620
whatever.

1107
00:40:44,220 --> 00:40:46,280
This is the quantity which is conserved.

1108
00:40:46,480 --> 00:40:48,740
I think the last time I called these delta q's,

1109
00:40:48,780 --> 00:40:49,560
I think I called them f.

1110
00:40:49,700 --> 00:40:50,940
I think I wrote that delta q

1111
00:40:51,960 --> 00:40:54,060
is equal to epsilon times f.

1112
00:40:54,660 --> 00:40:55,020
Well,

1113
00:40:55,020 --> 00:40:56,100
that's a redundant notation.

1114
00:40:56,200 --> 00:40:57,460
Just call it delta q

1115
00:40:57,460 --> 00:40:59,780
and forget the epsilon at the end of the story.

1116
00:41:00,460 --> 00:41:01,820
That's the conserved quantity,

1117
00:41:01,920 --> 00:41:03,760
the sum over all the variables

1118
00:41:04,280 --> 00:41:06,140
of the canonical momentum

1119
00:41:07,259 --> 00:41:09,820
multiplied by the small shift in the coordinate

1120
00:41:10,880 --> 00:41:12,900
when you do the symmetry operation.

1121
00:41:12,900 --> 00:41:15,920
So now we can write that down very quickly.

1122
00:41:16,520 --> 00:41:17,120
q,

1123
00:41:17,120 --> 00:41:18,280
for our case now,

1124
00:41:18,480 --> 00:41:19,900
is the integral over space.

1125
00:41:20,820 --> 00:41:22,260
That replaces sum.

1126
00:41:23,420 --> 00:41:25,320
What about p sub i?

1127
00:41:26,200 --> 00:41:29,780
That's the canonical momentum conjugate to phi.

1128
00:41:31,260 --> 00:41:32,360
There's two of them,

1129
00:41:32,360 --> 00:41:33,580
phi 1 and phi 2.

1130
00:41:34,380 --> 00:41:36,680
So we can write pi 1.

1131
00:41:38,260 --> 00:41:40,400
That's the canonical momentum conjugate

1132
00:41:40,400 --> 00:41:42,400
to the first field.

1133
00:41:43,040 --> 00:41:44,020
That's phi 1.

1134
00:41:44,220 --> 00:41:45,600
Times delta phi 1.

1135
00:41:45,800 --> 00:41:46,860
What is delta phi 1?

1136
00:41:46,980 --> 00:41:47,460
It's phi 2.

1137
00:41:51,520 --> 00:41:55,440
Plus pi 2 times delta phi 1.

1138
00:41:56,860 --> 00:41:59,480
But that's minus phi 1.

1139
00:41:59,660 --> 00:42:00,860
Did I say something wrong?

1140
00:42:01,480 --> 00:42:02,480
I think I did.

1141
00:42:03,460 --> 00:42:08,400
Minus pi 2 times the change here,

1142
00:42:08,500 --> 00:42:09,880
which is minus phi 1.

1143
00:42:12,380 --> 00:42:14,980
That's what Emmy Noether tells us

1144
00:42:14,980 --> 00:42:16,480
would be the conserved quantity,

1145
00:42:17,220 --> 00:42:19,080
conserved because of the symmetry.

1146
00:42:23,840 --> 00:42:24,520
Now,

1147
00:42:24,520 --> 00:42:26,900
let's go back to the original Lagrangian

1148
00:42:26,900 --> 00:42:27,980
that we had imagined.

1149
00:42:28,620 --> 00:42:30,600
The original Lagrangian that we imagined

1150
00:42:30,600 --> 00:42:34,000
involved time derivatives and space derivatives,

1151
00:42:34,440 --> 00:42:36,820
but in particular it involved time derivatives.

1152
00:42:37,140 --> 00:42:39,060
And the time derivatives were in the form

1153
00:42:40,260 --> 00:42:45,600
d phi by dt squared 1 half.

1154
00:42:46,800 --> 00:42:48,820
You can forget everything else for the moment.

1155
00:42:49,440 --> 00:42:52,780
This was the kinetic term in the Lagrangian.

1156
00:42:54,040 --> 00:42:56,240
Remember what the canonical momentum is.

1157
00:42:56,340 --> 00:42:58,340
The canonical momentum is the derivative

1158
00:42:58,340 --> 00:43:01,060
of the Lagrangian with respect to the velocity.

1159
00:43:02,100 --> 00:43:02,740
Well,

1160
00:43:02,740 --> 00:43:04,920
that's just the derivative of the Lagrangian

1161
00:43:04,920 --> 00:43:06,440
with respect to d phi dt,

1162
00:43:06,440 --> 00:43:07,820
and that's just d phi dt.

1163
00:43:08,720 --> 00:43:11,200
Pi 1 is d phi 1 by dt.

1164
00:43:12,560 --> 00:43:16,100
Pi 2 is d phi 2 by dt.

1165
00:43:18,500 --> 00:43:22,200
And so now we have an expression for the charge.

1166
00:43:22,400 --> 00:43:23,040
Here it is.

1167
00:43:26,320 --> 00:43:28,080
Equals integral over space

1168
00:43:30,640 --> 00:43:32,120
times pi 1,

1169
00:43:32,320 --> 00:43:33,460
which is,

1170
00:43:33,460 --> 00:43:35,700
let's just call it phi 1 dot,

1171
00:43:36,260 --> 00:43:37,620
times phi 2,

1172
00:43:39,000 --> 00:43:42,840
minus phi 2 dot times phi 1.

1173
00:43:52,520 --> 00:43:54,740
This quantity must be conserved.

1174
00:43:54,960 --> 00:43:55,700
We've proved it.

1175
00:43:55,740 --> 00:43:57,140
We've proved it a dozen times over.

1176
00:43:57,420 --> 00:44:00,280
We've proved it by proving a more general theorem.

1177
00:44:00,640 --> 00:44:03,020
Here's the more general theorem that this is conserved.

1178
00:44:03,420 --> 00:44:04,980
This is the conserved quantity,

1179
00:44:04,980 --> 00:44:06,700
and it's an integral over space.

1180
00:44:07,700 --> 00:44:08,180
Now,

1181
00:44:08,180 --> 00:44:10,640
to get a perspective on what this is,

1182
00:44:11,660 --> 00:44:12,940
on the meaning of it,

1183
00:44:13,020 --> 00:44:14,520
it's helpful to go back

1184
00:44:14,520 --> 00:44:16,020
to the analogy with the string.

1185
00:44:16,160 --> 00:44:17,160
I think we talked about this,

1186
00:44:17,160 --> 00:44:18,060
but let's do it again.

1187
00:44:20,560 --> 00:44:22,140
A string or a rope,

1188
00:44:22,140 --> 00:44:22,720
a jump rope,

1189
00:44:22,720 --> 00:44:23,600
something like that,

1190
00:44:23,720 --> 00:44:25,460
stretched between two points,

1191
00:44:25,940 --> 00:44:27,180
free to move around.

1192
00:44:27,320 --> 00:44:29,040
Our first version of the string

1193
00:44:29,560 --> 00:44:30,990
was that it was free

1194
00:44:30,990 --> 00:44:32,420
to move in the vertical plane.

1195
00:44:34,100 --> 00:44:36,370
Now I want to have it be

1196
00:44:36,370 --> 00:44:38,640
free also to move in the horizontal plane,

1197
00:44:39,420 --> 00:44:42,420
not move along the direction of the string,

1198
00:44:43,859 --> 00:44:45,800
but transverse to the direction of the string,

1199
00:44:45,860 --> 00:44:46,680
in both directions.

1200
00:44:47,380 --> 00:44:50,600
Let's call one direction phi 1

1201
00:44:50,600 --> 00:44:52,540
and the other direction phi 2.

1202
00:44:53,780 --> 00:44:55,620
Think of that thing in a model.

1203
00:44:55,820 --> 00:44:57,620
We're making up a model of a field theory now.

1204
00:44:57,700 --> 00:44:58,660
I don't want you to

1205
00:44:58,660 --> 00:44:59,620
think of a real jump rope.

1206
00:44:59,900 --> 00:45:00,520
I mean,

1207
00:45:00,520 --> 00:45:01,120
for the moment,

1208
00:45:01,120 --> 00:45:02,140
think of a real jump rope.

1209
00:45:02,140 --> 00:45:03,260
But ultimately,

1210
00:45:03,260 --> 00:45:05,520
we'll be thinking about mathematical fields

1211
00:45:05,520 --> 00:45:08,720
describing relativistic field theory and so forth.

1212
00:45:09,460 --> 00:45:11,800
But for our purposes right now,

1213
00:45:11,920 --> 00:45:14,020
you can actually think of phi 1 and phi 2

1214
00:45:14,020 --> 00:45:15,530
as the x and y coordinates

1215
00:45:15,530 --> 00:45:17,040
of a point on this string.

1216
00:45:19,160 --> 00:45:20,120
Now what is this?

1217
00:45:20,120 --> 00:45:21,200
What is phi 1 dot?

1218
00:45:22,620 --> 00:45:27,680
Phi 1 dot is the one component of the velocity.

1219
00:45:29,520 --> 00:45:32,120
So this is like the one component of the velocity.

1220
00:45:32,120 --> 00:45:33,220
This is the one component of the velocity

1221
00:45:33,220 --> 00:45:37,620
times the other component of position minus vice versa.

1222
00:45:38,300 --> 00:45:40,150
That should be familiar to many

1223
00:45:40,150 --> 00:45:42,000
of you as the angular momentum.

1224
00:45:43,220 --> 00:45:43,880
All right,

1225
00:45:43,880 --> 00:45:50,780
so if we really think about the mechanical analogy,

1226
00:45:51,080 --> 00:45:53,580
then the phi dots would be velocities,

1227
00:45:53,620 --> 00:45:56,180
and of course velocities are proportional to momenta,

1228
00:45:56,200 --> 00:45:57,480
ordinary momenta now,

1229
00:45:57,480 --> 00:45:59,120
just ordinary momenta.

1230
00:45:59,400 --> 00:46:02,040
And this would be like the x component

1231
00:46:02,120 --> 00:46:04,800
of momentum times y minus the y component

1232
00:46:04,800 --> 00:46:06,160
of momentum times x.

1233
00:46:07,140 --> 00:46:09,320
That would be called the angular momentum.

1234
00:46:09,680 --> 00:46:15,040
The angular momentum about an axis along the string.

1235
00:46:15,520 --> 00:46:18,880
So think of the jump rope being twirled around.

1236
00:46:19,960 --> 00:46:21,580
It has some angular momentum.

1237
00:46:23,660 --> 00:46:26,360
You don't really have to have anybody there twirling.

1238
00:46:26,360 --> 00:46:28,720
You can just have it anchored to some point,

1239
00:46:28,780 --> 00:46:30,080
and you give it a whirl,

1240
00:46:30,080 --> 00:46:31,660
and it continues to whirl,

1241
00:46:31,660 --> 00:46:33,160
and it doesn't stop unless there's friction,

1242
00:46:33,160 --> 00:46:33,580
of course.

1243
00:46:33,640 --> 00:46:34,580
Friction will stop it.

1244
00:46:34,780 --> 00:46:36,080
But in the absence of friction,

1245
00:46:37,200 --> 00:46:39,940
it will just continue to whirl around.

1246
00:46:40,300 --> 00:46:42,340
You can whirl it around with a node

1247
00:46:42,340 --> 00:46:44,580
so that half of it is over here,

1248
00:46:44,640 --> 00:46:45,880
the other half is over here,

1249
00:46:46,040 --> 00:46:48,520
and both of them are whirling around like this.

1250
00:46:48,940 --> 00:46:50,800
That would be positive angular momentum.

1251
00:46:51,080 --> 00:46:53,900
Going in the other way would be negative angular momentum.

1252
00:46:54,240 --> 00:46:54,480
Ooh,

1253
00:46:54,480 --> 00:46:55,040
I could do that.

1254
00:46:55,200 --> 00:46:56,420
I didn't know if I could do that.

1255
00:46:57,780 --> 00:46:58,800
I can't do this,

1256
00:46:58,800 --> 00:46:58,960
though.

1257
00:47:02,640 --> 00:47:03,120
Right,

1258
00:47:03,120 --> 00:47:05,380
so that's angular momentum about this axis.

1259
00:47:06,920 --> 00:47:07,980
That's the analog.

1260
00:47:08,100 --> 00:47:10,620
That's the analogy for charge.

1261
00:47:11,200 --> 00:47:12,080
That's the analogy,

1262
00:47:12,080 --> 00:47:13,220
the mechanical analogy,

1263
00:47:13,320 --> 00:47:14,900
in the jump rope case,

1264
00:47:14,900 --> 00:47:15,740
for charge.

1265
00:47:16,480 --> 00:47:18,400
But with or without the analogy,

1266
00:47:18,900 --> 00:47:20,120
this is the expression.

1267
00:47:20,880 --> 00:47:21,360
Now,

1268
00:47:21,360 --> 00:47:22,420
this can be written another way,

1269
00:47:22,520 --> 00:47:23,780
another compact way.

1270
00:47:23,840 --> 00:47:25,500
I'll write it in another compact way.

1271
00:47:25,580 --> 00:47:27,760
You can write it in terms of the complex components.

1272
00:47:29,060 --> 00:47:31,420
Let me write it in terms of the complex components.

1273
00:47:32,840 --> 00:47:35,300
It's also the integral of a space,

1274
00:47:35,300 --> 00:47:36,520
dx,

1275
00:47:40,960 --> 00:47:41,660
of,

1276
00:47:41,660 --> 00:47:43,160
I think there's an i,

1277
00:47:43,940 --> 00:47:46,080
and then there is a,

1278
00:47:47,580 --> 00:47:49,480
no phi 1 and phi 2,

1279
00:47:49,660 --> 00:47:53,500
but phi star dot phi

1280
00:47:56,560 --> 00:47:59,780
minus phi star phi dot.

1281
00:48:00,580 --> 00:48:03,280
If you work this out in terms of the components,

1282
00:48:03,520 --> 00:48:04,680
phi 1 and phi 2,

1283
00:48:05,220 --> 00:48:07,000
you get exactly the same thing.

1284
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:09,710
Notice that the two terms

1285
00:48:09,710 --> 00:48:11,420
are complex conjugates of each other.

1286
00:48:12,860 --> 00:48:13,880
And when you subtract,

1287
00:48:14,180 --> 00:48:16,600
what do you get when you subtract two complex conjugates?

1288
00:48:17,420 --> 00:48:18,140
Pure imaginary,

1289
00:48:18,140 --> 00:48:19,800
but if you multiply it by i,

1290
00:48:19,940 --> 00:48:20,920
it becomes pure real.

1291
00:48:22,840 --> 00:48:25,140
So you can also write this if you like.

1292
00:48:25,760 --> 00:48:27,280
I think there's a factor of 2.

1293
00:48:27,440 --> 00:48:28,480
There's a factor of 2,

1294
00:48:28,480 --> 00:48:28,960
if I remember.

1295
00:48:28,960 --> 00:48:31,100
Which is not terribly important.

1296
00:48:31,440 --> 00:48:32,640
If a thing is conserved,

1297
00:48:32,780 --> 00:48:34,880
then twice it is also conserved.

1298
00:48:35,160 --> 00:48:37,860
But technically I think there's a factor of 2 there.

1299
00:48:38,400 --> 00:48:41,080
We can also write this in another form

1300
00:48:41,080 --> 00:48:43,020
as just the imaginary part.

1301
00:48:44,140 --> 00:48:46,560
The imaginary part of the integral

1302
00:48:47,400 --> 00:48:49,960
of phi star dot phi.

1303
00:48:51,700 --> 00:48:53,740
If you take two things and you subtract

1304
00:48:53,740 --> 00:48:57,040
a thing from its complex conjugate,

1305
00:48:57,040 --> 00:49:00,280
it leaves over only the imaginary part.

1306
00:49:00,540 --> 00:49:03,240
So it's the imaginary part of phi star phi.

1307
00:49:03,920 --> 00:49:05,160
If you work out,

1308
00:49:05,160 --> 00:49:06,120
not phi star phi,

1309
00:49:06,260 --> 00:49:08,740
phi star dot times phi.

1310
00:49:10,280 --> 00:49:11,620
That's a way to write it.

1311
00:49:11,960 --> 00:49:12,760
It's a neat,

1312
00:49:12,760 --> 00:49:14,000
efficient way to write it.

1313
00:49:14,900 --> 00:49:17,320
And then we can just

1314
00:49:17,320 --> 00:49:19,740
concentrate on phi dot star phi

1315
00:49:19,740 --> 00:49:21,580
and remember at the end that

1316
00:49:21,580 --> 00:49:23,420
we should take its imaginary part.

1317
00:49:24,220 --> 00:49:26,920
And that defines the charge.

1318
00:49:26,920 --> 00:49:27,580
Alright,

1319
00:49:27,580 --> 00:49:30,440
it's just a notational device

1320
00:49:30,440 --> 00:49:32,830
that allows us to avoid

1321
00:49:32,830 --> 00:49:35,220
writing so many indices and things

1322
00:49:35,799 --> 00:49:37,199
and just write that the

1323
00:49:37,199 --> 00:49:38,600
charge density is the imaginary part

1324
00:49:38,600 --> 00:49:41,420
of the time derivative of phi star times phi.

1325
00:49:42,020 --> 00:49:45,540
What about the term with phi dot times phi star?

1326
00:49:46,980 --> 00:49:48,300
Did I forget to write it?

1327
00:49:51,340 --> 00:49:51,900
No.

1328
00:49:52,020 --> 00:49:55,120
When you take the imaginary part of something,

1329
00:49:55,120 --> 00:49:58,660
you subtract the thing from its complex conjugate.

1330
00:49:59,640 --> 00:50:01,060
So they're both there.

1331
00:50:02,940 --> 00:50:03,500
Okay,

1332
00:50:03,500 --> 00:50:11,200
that's a useful set of notations.

1333
00:50:12,300 --> 00:50:12,860
Now,

1334
00:50:12,860 --> 00:50:17,780
our goal is,

1335
00:50:17,780 --> 00:50:18,360
well,

1336
00:50:18,360 --> 00:50:18,960
first of all,

1337
00:50:19,040 --> 00:50:21,390
it's quite clear that this imaginary

1338
00:50:21,390 --> 00:50:23,740
part of phi star dot phi

1339
00:50:23,740 --> 00:50:24,940
is the charge density.

1340
00:50:25,120 --> 00:50:27,270
It's the thing that we integrate

1341
00:50:27,270 --> 00:50:29,420
over space to get the charge.

1342
00:50:30,020 --> 00:50:32,200
If this is indeed some sort of charge.

1343
00:50:32,460 --> 00:50:37,180
If indeed I've accurately identified what this object is

1344
00:50:37,180 --> 00:50:38,300
and it's some sort of charge,

1345
00:50:38,959 --> 00:50:40,900
then this thing in here is the charge density.

1346
00:50:41,180 --> 00:50:43,620
Or this thing in here is the charge density.

1347
00:50:44,860 --> 00:50:45,380
Rho.

1348
00:50:45,460 --> 00:50:46,960
What about the sign there?

1349
00:50:46,960 --> 00:50:48,040
Does that matter?

1350
00:50:48,400 --> 00:50:48,880
Well,

1351
00:50:48,880 --> 00:50:51,900
it doesn't really because you can either define the charge

1352
00:50:51,900 --> 00:50:52,940
or negative the charge.

1353
00:50:53,840 --> 00:50:54,360
Uh...

1354
00:50:55,300 --> 00:50:56,920
Somewhere along the line,

1355
00:50:56,920 --> 00:50:59,220
there was a convention,

1356
00:50:59,420 --> 00:51:00,940
which I've forgotten right now,

1357
00:51:01,080 --> 00:51:03,240
but it's strictly a convention of what you call positive

1358
00:51:03,240 --> 00:51:04,220
and what you call negative,

1359
00:51:04,220 --> 00:51:05,740
and it really doesn't matter.

1360
00:51:06,300 --> 00:51:08,280
I'm thinking that there's a minus sign

1361
00:51:08,280 --> 00:51:10,820
from the left-hand side to the imaginary notation.

1362
00:51:11,360 --> 00:51:12,760
That could well be.

1363
00:51:13,140 --> 00:51:13,160
So,

1364
00:51:13,160 --> 00:51:15,000
um...

1365
00:51:15,860 --> 00:51:16,340
Let's...

1366
00:51:18,340 --> 00:51:19,200
Could well be.

1367
00:51:19,200 --> 00:51:20,740
I'm not going to try to track it now.

1368
00:51:20,840 --> 00:51:21,440
It'll waste time.

1369
00:51:21,840 --> 00:51:23,820
But it's one sign or the other.

1370
00:51:23,820 --> 00:51:24,780
And the important point...

1371
00:51:24,780 --> 00:51:26,360
The important fact is that it's not important.

1372
00:51:27,120 --> 00:51:28,640
It's important to be consistent,

1373
00:51:29,259 --> 00:51:32,460
but it's not important when you're making your definition

1374
00:51:32,460 --> 00:51:33,980
of what you want to call charge

1375
00:51:33,980 --> 00:51:35,500
to fix one sign or the other.

1376
00:51:35,560 --> 00:51:37,120
You fix a sign and then you stick with it.

1377
00:51:37,400 --> 00:51:38,980
So let's use this,

1378
00:51:38,980 --> 00:51:39,380
uh...

1379
00:51:39,380 --> 00:51:42,000
Let's use this notation with the minus sign here.

1380
00:51:43,480 --> 00:51:46,520
I hate carrying around the minus sign.

1381
00:51:46,960 --> 00:51:47,400
Oh,

